IAM role ARNs have the format arn:partition:iam::account:role/role-name-with-path. For example: arn:aws:iam::111122223333:role/Admin.

For more information, see IAM ARNs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:
The language code that represents the language of the entries in your custom vocabulary. Each custom vocabulary must contain terms in only one language.

A custom vocabulary can only be used to transcribe files in the same language as the custom vocabulary. For example, if you create a custom vocabulary using US English (en-US), you can only apply this custom vocabulary to files that contain English audio.

For a list of supported languages and their associated language codes, refer to the Supported languages table.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: phrases
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:
Use this parameter if you want to create your custom vocabulary by including all desired terms, as comma-separated values, within your request. The other option for creating your custom vocabulary is to save your entries in a text file and upload them to an Amazon S3 bucket, then specify the location of your file using the VocabularyFileUri parameter.

Note that if you include Phrases in your request, you cannot use VocabularyFileUri; you must choose one or the other.

Each language has a character set that contains all allowed characters for that specific language. If you use unsupported characters, your custom vocabulary filter request fails. Refer to Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies to get the character set for your language.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:
Adds one or more custom tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new custom vocabulary at the time you create this new custom vocabulary.

To learn more about using tags with Amazon Transcribe, refer to Tagging resources.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:

Here’s an example URI path: s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/my-vocab-file.txt

Note that if you include VocabularyFileUri in your request, you cannot use the Phrases flag; you must choose one or the other.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of an IAM role that has permissions to access the Amazon S3 bucket that contains your input files (in this case, your custom vocabulary filter). If the role that you specify doesn’t have the appropriate permissions to access the specified Amazon S3 location, your request fails.

IAM role ARNs have the format arn:partition:iam::account:role/role-name-with-path. For example: arn:aws:iam::111122223333:role/Admin.

For more information, see IAM ARNs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The language code that represents the language of the entries in your vocabulary filter. Each custom vocabulary filter must contain terms in only one language.

A custom vocabulary filter can only be used to transcribe files in the same language as the filter. For example, if you create a custom vocabulary filter using US English (en-US), you can only apply this filter to files that contain English audio.

For a list of supported languages and their associated language codes, refer to the Supported languages table.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
Adds one or more custom tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new custom vocabulary filter at the time you create this new vocabulary filter.

To learn more about using tags with Amazon Transcribe, refer to Tagging resources.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location of the text file that contains your custom vocabulary filter terms. The URI must be located in the same Amazon Web Services Region as the resource you’re calling.

Here’s an example URI path: s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/my-vocab-filter-file.txt

Note that if you include VocabularyFilterFileUri in your request, you cannot use Words; you must choose one or the other.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
A unique name, chosen by you, for your new custom vocabulary filter.

This name is case sensitive, cannot contain spaces, and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. If you try to create a new custom vocabulary filter with the same name as an existing custom vocabulary filter, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: words
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
Use this parameter if you want to create your custom vocabulary filter by including all desired terms, as comma-separated values, within your request. The other option for creating your vocabulary filter is to save your entries in a text file and upload them to an Amazon S3 bucket, then specify the location of your file using the VocabularyFilterFileUri parameter.

Note that if you include Words in your request, you cannot use VocabularyFilterFileUri; you must choose one or the other.

Each language has a character set that contains all allowed characters for that specific language. If you use unsupported characters, your custom vocabulary filter request fails. Refer to Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies to get the character set for your language.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: If VocabularyState is FAILED, FailureReason contains information about why the medical transcription job request failed. See also: Common Errors.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code you selected for your custom medical vocabulary. US English (en-US) is the only language supported with Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
The date and time you created your custom medical vocabulary.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.761000-07:00 represents 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The name you chose for your custom medical vocabulary.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The processing state of your custom medical vocabulary. If the state is READY, you can use the custom vocabulary in a StartMedicalTranscriptionJob request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code that represents the language of the entries in your custom vocabulary. US English (en-US) is the only language supported with Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
Adds one or more custom tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new custom medical vocabulary at the time you create this new custom vocabulary.

To learn more about using tags with Amazon Transcribe, refer to Tagging resources.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location (URI) of the text file that contains your custom medical vocabulary. The URI must be in the same Amazon Web Services Region as the resource you’re calling.

Here’s an example URI path: s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/my-vocab-file.txt

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
A unique name, chosen by you, for your new custom medical vocabulary.

This name is case sensitive, cannot contain spaces, and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. If you try to create a new custom medical vocabulary with the same name as an existing custom medical vocabulary, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: baseModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The Amazon Transcribe standard language model, or base model, you specified when creating your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: Lists your data access role ARN (Amazon Resource Name) and the Amazon S3 locations you provided for your training (S3Uri) and tuning (TuningDataS3Uri) data.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The language code you selected for your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The name of your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The status of your custom language model. When the status displays as COMPLETED, your model is ready to use.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: baseModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
The Amazon Transcribe standard language model, or base model, used to create your custom language model. Amazon Transcribe offers two options for base models: Wideband and Narrowband.

If the audio you want to transcribe has a sample rate of 16,000 Hz or greater, choose WideBand. To transcribe audio with a sample rate less than 16,000 Hz, choose NarrowBand.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
Contains the Amazon S3 location of the training data you want to use to create a new custom language model, and permissions to access this location.

When using InputDataConfig, you must include these sub-parameters: S3Uri, which is the Amazon S3 location of your training data, and DataAccessRoleArn, which is the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the role that has permission to access your specified Amazon S3 location. You can optionally include TuningDataS3Uri, which is the Amazon S3 location of your tuning data. If you specify different Amazon S3 locations for training and tuning data, the ARN you use must have permissions to access both locations.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
The language code that represents the language of your model. Each custom language model must contain terms in only one language, and the language you select for your custom language model must match the language of your training and tuning data.

For a list of supported languages and their associated language codes, refer to the Supported languages table. Note that US English (en-US) is the only language supported with Amazon Transcribe Medical.

A custom language model can only be used to transcribe files in the same language as the model. For example, if you create a custom language model using US English (en-US), you can only apply this model to files that contain English audio.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
A unique name, chosen by you, for your custom language model.

This name is case sensitive, cannot contain spaces, and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. If you try to create a new custom language model with the same name as an existing custom language model, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
Adds one or more custom tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new custom language model at the time you create this new model.

To learn more about using tags with Amazon Transcribe, refer to Tagging resources.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: categoryProperties
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract: Provides you with the properties of your new category, including its associated rules.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract:
A unique name, chosen by you, for your Call Analytics category. It’s helpful to use a detailed naming system that will make sense to you in the future. For example, it’s better to use sentiment-positive-last30seconds for a category over a generic name like test-category.

Category names are case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: inputType
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract:
Choose whether you want to create a real-time or a post-call category for your Call Analytics transcription.

Specifying POST_CALL assigns your category to post-call transcriptions; categories with this input type cannot be applied to streaming (real-time) transcriptions.

Specifying REAL_TIME assigns your category to streaming transcriptions; categories with this input type cannot be applied to post-call transcriptions.

If you do not include InputType, your category is created as a post-call category by default.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: rules
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract: Rules define a Call Analytics category. When creating a new category, you must create between 1 and 20 rules for that category. For each rule, you specify a filter you want applied to the attributes of a call. For example, you can choose a sentiment filter that detects if a customer’s sentiment was positive during the last 30 seconds of the call.

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: piiEntityTypes
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract: Specify which types of personally identifiable information (PII) you want to redact in your transcript. You can include as many types as you’d like, or you can select ALL. If you do not include PiiEntityTypes in your request, all PII is redacted.

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: redactionOutput
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract:
Specify if you want only a redacted transcript, or if you want a redacted and an unredacted transcript.

When you choose redacted Amazon Transcribe creates only a redacted transcript.

When you choose redacted_and_unredacted Amazon Transcribe creates a redacted and an unredacted transcript (as two separate files).

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: redactionType
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract: Specify the category of information you want to redact; PII (personally identifiable information) is the only valid value. You can use PiiEntityTypes to choose which types of PII you want to redact. If you do not include PiiEntityTypes in your request, all PII is redacted.

Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.name: channelId
Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.abstract: Specify the audio channel you want to define.

Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.name: participantRole
Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.abstract: Specify the speaker you want to define. Omitting this parameter is equivalent to specifying both participants.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract: The name of the Call Analytics category. Category names are case sensitive and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: createTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics category was created.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.761000-07:00 represents 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: inputType
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract: The input type associated with the specified category. POST_CALL refers to a category that is applied to batch transcriptions; REAL_TIME refers to a category that is applied to streaming transcriptions.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: lastUpdateTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics category was last updated.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-05T12:45:32.691000-07:00 represents 12:45 PM UTC-7 on May 5, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: rules
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract: The rules used to define a Call Analytics category. Each category can have between 1 and 20 rules.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.name: feature
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.abstract: Indicates the type of analytics feature that was skipped during the analysis of a call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.name: message
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.abstract: Contains additional information or a message explaining why a specific analytics feature was skipped during the analysis of a call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.name: reasonCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.abstract: Provides a code indicating the reason why a specific analytics feature was skipped during the analysis of a call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: callAnalyticsJobDetails
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: Provides detailed information about a call analytics job, including information about skipped analytics features.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: callAnalyticsJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: The name of the Call Analytics job. Job names are case sensitive and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: callAnalyticsJobStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract:
Provides the status of your Call Analytics job.

If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished and you can find the results at the location specified in TranscriptFileUri (or RedactedTranscriptFileUri, if you requested transcript redaction). If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your transcription job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics job finished processing.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:33:13.922000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:33 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics job request was made.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.761000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: If CallAnalyticsJobStatus is FAILED, FailureReason contains information about why the Call Analytics job failed. See also: Common Errors.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: The language code used to create your Call Analytics transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: startTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract:
The date and time your Call Analytics job began processing.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.789000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: contentRedaction
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract: Makes it possible to redact or flag specified personally identifiable information (PII) in your transcript. If you use ContentRedaction, you must also include the sub-parameters: RedactionOutput and RedactionType. You can optionally include PiiEntityTypes to choose which types of PII you want to redact.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: languageIdSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract:
If using automatic language identification in your request and you want to apply a custom language model, a custom vocabulary, or a custom vocabulary filter, include LanguageIdSettings with the relevant sub-parameters (VocabularyName, LanguageModelName, and VocabularyFilterName).

LanguageIdSettings supports two to five language codes. Each language code you include can have an associated custom language model, custom vocabulary, and custom vocabulary filter. The language codes that you specify must match the languages of the associated custom language models, custom vocabularies, and custom vocabulary filters.

It’s recommended that you include LanguageOptions when using LanguageIdSettings to ensure that the correct language dialect is identified. For example, if you specify a custom vocabulary that is in en-US but Amazon Transcribe determines that the language spoken in your media is en-AU, your custom vocabulary is not applied to your transcription. If you include LanguageOptions and include en-US as the only English language dialect, your custom vocabulary is applied to your transcription.

If you want to include a custom language model, custom vocabulary, or custom vocabulary filter with your request but do not want to use automatic language identification, use instead the parameter with the LanguageModelName, VocabularyName, or VocabularyFilterName sub-parameters.

For a list of languages supported with Call Analytics, refer to Supported languages and language-specific features.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: languageModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract:
The name of the custom language model you want to use when processing your Call Analytics job. Note that custom language model names are case sensitive.

The language of the specified custom language model must match the language code that you specify in your transcription request. If the languages do not match, the custom language model isn’t applied. There are no errors or warnings associated with a language mismatch.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: languageOptions
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract:
You can specify two or more language codes that represent the languages you think may be present in your media. Including more than five is not recommended. If you’re unsure what languages are present, do not include this parameter.

Including language options can improve the accuracy of language identification.

For a list of languages supported with Call Analytics, refer to the Supported languages table.

To transcribe speech in Modern Standard Arabic (ar-SA), your media file must be encoded at a sample rate of 16,000 Hz or higher.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: summarization
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract: Contains GenerateAbstractiveSummary, which is a required parameter if you want to enable Generative call summarization in your Call Analytics request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: vocabularyFilterMethod
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract:
Specify how you want your custom vocabulary filter applied to your transcript.

To replace words with ***, choose mask.

To delete words, choose remove.

To flag words without changing them, choose tag.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract:
The name of the custom vocabulary filter you want to include in your Call Analytics transcription request. Custom vocabulary filter names are case sensitive.

Note that if you include VocabularyFilterName in your request, you must also include VocabularyFilterMethod.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract: The name of the custom vocabulary you want to include in your Call Analytics transcription request. Custom vocabulary names are case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobDet.name: skipped
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobDet.abstract:
Contains information about any skipped analytics features during the analysis of a call analytics job.

This array lists all the analytics features that were skipped, along with their corresponding reason code and message.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: callAnalyticsJobDetails
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: Provides detailed information about a call analytics job, including information about skipped analytics features.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: callAnalyticsJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: The name of the Call Analytics job. Job names are case sensitive and must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: callAnalyticsJobStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
Provides the status of the specified Call Analytics job.

If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished and you can find the results at the location specified in TranscriptFileUri (or RedactedTranscriptFileUri, if you requested transcript redaction). If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your transcription job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: channelDefinitions
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: Indicates which speaker is on which channel.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics job finished processing.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:33:13.922000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:33 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics job request was made.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.761000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) you included in your request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
If CallAnalyticsJobStatus is FAILED, FailureReason contains information about why the Call Analytics job request failed.

The FailureReason field contains one of the following values:

  • Unsupported media format.

    The media format specified in MediaFormat isn’t valid. Refer to refer to the MediaFormat parameter for a list of supported formats.

  • The media format provided does not match the detected media format.

    The media format specified in MediaFormat doesn’t match the format of the input file. Check the media format of your media file and correct the specified value.

  • Invalid sample rate for audio file.

    The sample rate specified in MediaSampleRateHertz isn’t valid. The sample rate must be between 8,000 and 48,000 hertz.

  • The sample rate provided does not match the detected sample rate.

    The sample rate specified in MediaSampleRateHertz doesn’t match the sample rate detected in your input media file. Check the sample rate of your media file and correct the specified value.

  • Invalid file size: file size too large.

    The size of your media file is larger than what Amazon Transcribe can process. For more information, refer to Service quotas.

  • Invalid number of channels: number of channels too large.

    Your audio contains more channels than Amazon Transcribe is able to process. For more information, refer to Service quotas.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: identifiedLanguageScore
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
The confidence score associated with the language identified in your media file.

Confidence scores are values between 0 and 1; a larger value indicates a higher probability that the identified language correctly matches the language spoken in your media.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
The language code used to create your Call Analytics job. For a list of supported languages and their associated language codes, refer to the Supported languages table.

If you do not know the language spoken in your media file, you can omit this field and let Amazon Transcribe automatically identify the language of your media. To improve the accuracy of language identification, you can include several language codes and Amazon Transcribe chooses the closest match for your transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: Provides the Amazon S3 location of the media file you used in your Call Analytics request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: mediaSampleRateHertz
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: The sample rate, in hertz, of the audio track in your input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: Provides information on any additional settings that were included in your request. Additional settings include content redaction and language identification settings.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: startTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
The date and time the specified Call Analytics job began processing.

Timestamps are in the format YYYY-MM-DD'T'HH:MM:SS.SSSSSS-UTC. For example, 2022-05-04T12:32:58.789000-07:00 represents a transcription job that started processing at 12:32 PM UTC-7 on May 4, 2022.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: transcript
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract: Provides you with the Amazon S3 URI you can use to access your transcript.

Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.name: endTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.abstract: The time, in milliseconds, when Amazon Transcribe stops searching for the specified criteria in your audio. If you include EndTime in your request, you must also include StartTime.

Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.name: first
Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.abstract: The time, in milliseconds, from the start of your media file until the specified value. Amazon Transcribe searches for your specified criteria in this time segment.

Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.name: last
Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.abstract: The time, in milliseconds, from the specified value until the end of your media file. Amazon Transcribe searches for your specified criteria in this time segment.

Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.name: startTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.abstract: The time, in milliseconds, when Amazon Transcribe starts searching for the specified criteria in your audio. If you include StartTime in your request, you must also include EndTime.

Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.name: AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeAbsoluteTimeRange.h.abstract:
A time range, in milliseconds, between two points in your media file.

You can use StartTime and EndTime to search a custom segment. For example, setting StartTime to 10000 and EndTime to 50000 only searches for your specified criteria in the audio contained between the 10,000 millisecond mark and the 50,000 millisecond mark of your media file. You must use StartTime and EndTime as a set; that is, if you include one, you must include both.

You can use also First to search from the start of the audio until the time that you specify, or Last to search from the time that you specify until the end of the audio. For example, setting First to 50000 only searches for your specified criteria in the audio contained between the start of the media file to the 50,000 millisecond mark. You can use First and Last independently of each other.

If you prefer to use percentage instead of milliseconds, see .

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.name: AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJob.ht.abstract:
Provides detailed information about a Call Analytics job.

To view the job’s status, refer to CallAnalyticsJobStatus. If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished. You can find your completed transcript at the URI specified in TranscriptFileUri. If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your transcription job failed.

If you enabled personally identifiable information (PII) redaction, the redacted transcript appears at the location specified in RedactedTranscriptFileUri.

If you chose to redact the audio in your media file, you can find your redacted media file at the location specified in the RedactedMediaFileUri field of your response.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobDet.name: AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobDetails
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobDet.abstract: Contains details about a call analytics job, including information about skipped analytics features.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.name: AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSet.abstract: Provides additional optional settings for your request, including content redaction, automatic language identification; allows you to apply custom language models, custom vocabulary filters, and custom vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSummary
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: Provides detailed information about a specific Call Analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.name: AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippedFeature
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsSkippe.abstract:
Represents a skipped analytics feature during the analysis of a call analytics job.

The Feature field indicates the type of analytics feature that was skipped.

The Message field contains additional information or a message explaining why the analytics feature was skipped.

The ReasonCode field provides a code indicating the reason why the analytics feature was skipped.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties
Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract: Provides you with the properties of the Call Analytics category you specified in your request. This includes the list of rules that define the specified category.

Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.name: AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition
Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.abstract: Makes it possible to specify which speaker is on which channel. For example, if your agent is the first participant to speak, you would set ChannelId to 0 (to indicate the first channel) and ParticipantRole to AGENT (to indicate that it’s the agent speaking).

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: AWSTranscribeContentRedaction
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract: Makes it possible to redact or flag specified personally identifiable information (PII) in your transcript. If you use ContentRedaction, you must also include the sub-parameters: RedactionOutput and RedactionType. You can optionally include PiiEntityTypes to choose which types of PII you want to redact.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.name: AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.abstract:
Contains the Amazon S3 location of the training data you want to use to create a new custom language model, and permissions to access this location.

When using InputDataConfig, you must include these sub-parameters: S3Uri and DataAccessRoleArn. You can optionally include TuningDataS3Uri.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..name: AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..abstract:
Flag the presence or absence of interruptions in your Call Analytics transcription output.

Rules using InterruptionFilter are designed to match:

  • Instances where an agent interrupts a customer

  • Instances where a customer interrupts an agent

  • Either participant interrupting the other

  • A lack of interruptions

See Rule criteria for post-call categories for usage examples.

Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.name: AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.abstract:
Makes it possible to control how your transcription job is processed. Currently, the only JobExecutionSettings modification you can choose is enabling job queueing using the AllowDeferredExecution sub-parameter.

If you include JobExecutionSettings in your request, you must also include the sub-parameters: AllowDeferredExecution and DataAccessRoleArn.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageCodeItem.ht.name: AWSTranscribeLanguageCodeItem
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageCodeItem.ht.abstract: Provides information on the speech contained in a discreet utterance when multi-language identification is enabled in your request. This utterance represents a block of speech consisting of one language, preceded or followed by a block of speech in a different language.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..name: AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..abstract:
If using automatic language identification in your request and you want to apply a custom language model, a custom vocabulary, or a custom vocabulary filter, include LanguageIdSettings with the relevant sub-parameters (VocabularyName, LanguageModelName, and VocabularyFilterName). Note that multi-language identification (IdentifyMultipleLanguages) doesn’t support custom language models.

LanguageIdSettings supports two to five language codes. Each language code you include can have an associated custom language model, custom vocabulary, and custom vocabulary filter. The language codes that you specify must match the languages of the associated custom language models, custom vocabularies, and custom vocabulary filters.

It’s recommended that you include LanguageOptions when using LanguageIdSettings to ensure that the correct language dialect is identified. For example, if you specify a custom vocabulary that is in en-US but Amazon Transcribe determines that the language spoken in your media is en-AU, your custom vocabulary is not applied to your transcription. If you include LanguageOptions and include en-US as the only English language dialect, your custom vocabulary is applied to your transcription.

If you want to include a custom language model with your request but do not want to use automatic language identification, use instead the parameter with the LanguageModelName sub-parameter. If you want to include a custom vocabulary or a custom vocabulary filter (or both) with your request but do not want to use automatic language identification, use instead the parameter with the VocabularyName or VocabularyFilterName (or both) sub-parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html.name: AWSTranscribeLanguageModel
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html.abstract:
Provides information about a custom language model, including:

  • The base model name

  • When the model was created

  • The location of the files used to train the model

  • When the model was last modified

  • The name you chose for the model

  • The model’s language

  • The model’s processing state

  • Any available upgrades for the base model

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedia.html.name: AWSTranscribeMedia
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedia.html.abstract:
Describes the Amazon S3 location of the media file you want to use in your request.

For information on supported media formats, refer to the MediaFormat parameter or the Media formats section in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeChanne.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeChannelDefinition
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeChanne.abstract: Indicates which speaker is on which channel. The options are CLINICIAN and PATIENT

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJob.ht.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJob.ht.abstract:
Provides detailed information about a Medical Scribe job.

To view the status of the specified Medical Scribe job, check the MedicalScribeJobStatus field. If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished and you can find the results at the locations specified in MedicalScribeOutput. If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your Medical Scribe job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJobSum.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJobSummary
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeJobSum.abstract: Provides detailed information about a specific Medical Scribe job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeOutput.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeOutput
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeOutput.abstract: The location of the output of your Medical Scribe job. ClinicalDocumentUri holds the Amazon S3 URI for the Clinical Document and TranscriptFileUri holds the Amazon S3 URI for the Transcript.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeSettin.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalScribeSettin.abstract: Makes it possible to control how your Medical Scribe job is processed using a MedicalScribeSettings object. Specify ChannelIdentification if ChannelDefinitions are set. Enabled ShowSpeakerLabels if ChannelIdentification and ChannelDefinitions are not set. One and only one of ChannelIdentification and ShowSpeakerLabels must be set. If ShowSpeakerLabels is set, MaxSpeakerLabels must also be set. Use Settings to specify a vocabulary or vocabulary filter or both using VocabularyName, VocabularyFilterName. VocabularyFilterMethod must be specified if VocabularyFilterName is set.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscript.h.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscript
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscript.h.abstract: Provides you with the Amazon S3 URI you can use to access your transcript.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract:
Provides detailed information about a medical transcription job.

To view the status of the specified medical transcription job, check the TranscriptionJobStatus field. If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished and you can find the results at the location specified in TranscriptFileUri. If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your transcription job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptionJobSummary
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: Provides detailed information about a specific medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptionSetting
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: Allows additional optional settings in your request, including channel identification, alternative transcriptions, and speaker partitioning. You can use that to apply custom vocabularies to your medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeModelSettings.html.name: AWSTranscribeModelSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeModelSettings.html.abstract:
Provides the name of the custom language model that was included in the specified transcription job.

Only use ModelSettings with the LanguageModelName sub-parameter if you’re not using automatic language identification (). If using LanguageIdSettings in your request, this parameter contains a LanguageModelName sub-parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.name: AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.abstract:
Flag the presence or absence of periods of silence in your Call Analytics transcription output.

Rules using NonTalkTimeFilter are designed to match:

  • The presence of silence at specified periods throughout the call

  • The presence of speech at specified periods throughout the call

See Rule criteria for post-call categories for usage examples.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.name: AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.abstract:
A time range, in percentage, between two points in your media file.

You can use StartPercentage and EndPercentage to search a custom segment. For example, setting StartPercentage to 10 and EndPercentage to 50 only searches for your specified criteria in the audio contained between the 10 percent mark and the 50 percent mark of your media file.

You can use also First to search from the start of the media file until the time that you specify. Or use Last to search from the time that you specify until the end of the media file. For example, setting First to 10 only searches for your specified criteria in the audio contained in the first 10 percent of the media file.

If you prefer to use milliseconds instead of percentage, see .

Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html.name: AWSTranscribeRule
Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html.abstract:
A rule is a set of criteria that you can specify to flag an attribute in your Call Analytics output. Rules define a Call Analytics category.

Rules can include these parameters: , , , and .

To learn more about Call Analytics rules and categories, see Creating categories for post-call transcriptions and Creating categories for real-time transcriptions.

To learn more about Call Analytics, see Analyzing call center audio with Call Analytics.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.abstract:
Flag the presence or absence of specific sentiments detected in your Call Analytics transcription output.

Rules using SentimentFilter are designed to match:

  • The presence or absence of a positive sentiment felt by the customer, agent, or both at specified points in the call

  • The presence or absence of a negative sentiment felt by the customer, agent, or both at specified points in the call

  • The presence or absence of a neutral sentiment felt by the customer, agent, or both at specified points in the call

  • The presence or absence of a mixed sentiment felt by the customer, the agent, or both at specified points in the call

See Rule criteria for post-call categories for usage examples.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html.name: AWSTranscribeSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html.abstract: Allows additional optional settings in your request, including channel identification, alternative transcriptions, and speaker partitioning. You can use that to apply custom vocabularies to your transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitles.html.name: AWSTranscribeSubtitles
Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitles.html.abstract:
Generate subtitles for your media file with your transcription request.

You can choose a start index of 0 or 1, and you can specify either WebVTT or SubRip (or both) as your output format.

Note that your subtitle files are placed in the same location as your transcription output.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.name: AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput
Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.abstract: Provides information about your subtitle file, including format, start index, and Amazon S3 location.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSummarization.html.name: AWSTranscribeSummarization
Classes/AWSTranscribeSummarization.html.abstract: Contains GenerateAbstractiveSummary, which is a required parameter if you want to enable Generative call summarization in your Call Analytics request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html.name: AWSTranscribeTag
Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html.abstract:
Adds metadata, in the form of a key:value pair, to the specified resource.

For example, you could add the tag Department:Sales to a resource to indicate that it pertains to your organization’s sales department. You can also use tags for tag-based access control.

To learn more about tagging, see Tagging resources.

Classes/AWSTranscribeToxicityDetectionSe.name: AWSTranscribeToxicityDetectionSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeToxicityDetectionSe.abstract: Contains ToxicityCategories, which is a required parameter if you want to enable toxicity detection (ToxicityDetection) in your transcription request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html.name: AWSTranscribeTranscript
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html.abstract: Provides you with the Amazon S3 URI you can use to access your transcript.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract:
Flag the presence or absence of specific words or phrases detected in your Call Analytics transcription output.

Rules using TranscriptFilter are designed to match:

  • Custom words or phrases spoken by the agent, the customer, or both

  • Custom words or phrases not spoken by the agent, the customer, or either

  • Custom words or phrases that occur at a specific time frame

See Rule criteria for post-call categories and Rule criteria for streaming categories for usage examples.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract:
Provides detailed information about a transcription job.

To view the status of the specified transcription job, check the TranscriptionJobStatus field. If the status is COMPLETED, the job is finished and you can find the results at the location specified in TranscriptFileUri. If the status is FAILED, FailureReason provides details on why your transcription job failed.

If you enabled content redaction, the redacted transcript can be found at the location specified in RedactedTranscriptFileUri.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSummary
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: Provides detailed information about a specific transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeVocabularyFilterInf.name: AWSTranscribeVocabularyFilterInfo
Classes/AWSTranscribeVocabularyFilterInf.abstract: Provides information about a custom vocabulary filter, including the language of the filter, when it was last modified, and its name.

Classes/AWSTranscribeVocabularyInfo.html.name: AWSTranscribeVocabularyInfo
Classes/AWSTranscribeVocabularyInfo.html.abstract: Provides information about a custom vocabulary, including the language of the custom vocabulary, when it was last modified, its name, and the processing state.

Classes/AWSTranscribe.html.name: AWSTranscribe
Classes/AWSTranscribe.html.abstract:
Amazon Transcribe offers three main types of batch transcription: Standard, Medical, and Call Analytics.

  • Standard transcriptions are the most common option. Refer to for details.

  • Medical transcriptions are tailored to medical professionals and incorporate medical terms. A common use case for this service is transcribing doctor-patient dialogue into after-visit notes. Refer to for details.

  • Call Analytics transcriptions are designed for use with call center audio on two different channels; if you’re looking for insight into customer service calls, use this option. Refer to for details.
